en: Histoire de Don Quichotte de la Manche
Don Quichotte s'exalte à la lecture des romans de Chevalerie
1.1 DQ at his library reading chivalric novels
Printed in black on sepia background with reserves in white

Don Quixote at his library reading chivalry books; also arms in the room.Excellent drawing.Remarkable combination of lithographic pencil (drawing and shading), sepia background and white reserves to represent a perfect atmosphere.Good precedent for Doré's don Quixote.Illustration of great quality.It can be compared with Johannot's illustration (Paris: Dubuchett, 1836-37).

Canonical image; don Quixote on Rocinante and Sancho on his donkey with their village in the background; don Quixote's second sally or first sally of both characters together.Don Quixote is wearing the basin on his head, although he has not won it yet.It can be compared with Johannot's illustration (Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37).

Don Quixote in bed dreaming his adventures; these appear in different scenes, all framed by clouds: don Quixote and the giants (windmills); don Quixote and the lady of a castle (Maritornes); the enchanter Frestón; a tournament (don Quixote against Tosilos); don Gaiferos and Melisendra; and the armies (flock of sheep).Image in keeping with Romanticism taste; it is represented don Quixote's fantasy, not the reality.Very original headpiece format.
3.4 DQ knighted at inn by innkeeper
Printed in black on sepia background with reserves in white

At the inn, don Quixote, knelt down, is knighted by the innkeeper; also two "ladies" (doña Molinera and doña Tolosa) and a boy holding a candle.Well-known scene; resolved with a traditional composition.Excellent combination of lithographic pencil (drawing and shading), sepia background and reserves in white to create a very remarkable atmosphere and light/shadow effects.

1 - "Esas lindas muchachas, que procuran contenerse la risa; ese ventero socarrón; ese Don Quijote en actitud orante, y ese rapaz murillesco que aguanta la vela, están vistos por un artista parisiense que probablemente ha leído el Viaje aEspaña de TeófiloGautier" (Givanel 210-212).
Combat contre les moulins à vent
Printed in black on sepia background with reserves in white

In the foreground, Sancho shouting to don Quixote to stop him.In the background, don Quixote ready to attack one windmill.Good picturesque details: Sancho and his donkey, the windmills...Excellent drawing.
Don Quichotte fond sur un troupeau de Moutons
18.1 Adventure of the flock of sheep (rebaños)
Printed in black on sepia background with reserves in white

In the foreground, don Quixote attacking a flock of sheep; scene resolved with drama (notice the realism of the sheeps).In the background, Sancho (left) and a shepherd ready to stone don Quixote (right).Very close to Johannot's illustration (Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37).Doré almost copies this composition (Paris: Hachette, 1863).
21.3 Adventure of the helmet of Mambrino
Printed in black on sepia background with reserves in white

The barber throws himself from his mule to avoid don Quixote's attack and run away; in the background, Sancho.Excellent composition; notice the diagonal from don Quixote's face, along the lance (indicating Rocinante's movement), to the barber's head.Excellent illustration.
43.2 Maritornes and innkeeper’s daughter hang DQ from window by a hand
Printed in black on sepia background with reserves in white

Don Quixote on the point of falling from Rocinante and remaining hanged by his hand tied to a window; Rocinante is moving to smell one of the mares of four travelers who have just arrived to the inn.Well-known scene, but this illustration is remarkable.Good setting; picturesque, but not Spanish.
